Introduction

The Mission

Bellabeats mission is to deliver wellness products designed for women. It is targeted for young to middle-aged women who live active lifestyles, care about their health as well as make informed choices every day in terms of their diet, workout routine, meditation, and hydration.

The Products

Bellabeats product line includes a Bellabeat app, a Bellabeat Leaf wellness tracker, a smartwatch, a smart water bottle, and a subscription-based membership program for users.

The Task & The Dataset

My job, as an imaginary junior data analyst, is to provide primary and secondary stakeholders within the company with insightful recommendations regarding one product in their line of wellness products. For this case study I have decided to go with the smartwatch and have been tasked to use a Kaggle dataset for FitBit Fitness Tracker (under CC0: Public Domain license) as a benchmark since it is also a smartwatch and collects similar data to Bellabeats smartwatch.

My job is to give sound advice and recommend improvements to the current business plan by applying a data-driven decision-making framework.

This process will require me to ask the right questions, prepare the dataset, and choose crucial metrics to analyze. Next, I am going to clean and analyze the clean dataset. Afterward, I am going to visualize and finally share my recommendation for further actions to stakeholders.

The People

Primary stakeholders include: Urka Sren: Bellabeats co-founder and Chief Creative Officer. Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeats co-founder; a key member of the Bellabeat executive team.

Secondary stakeholders: Bellabeat marketing analytics team (this is the team I am a part of).

Step 1: Assessing datas integrity and veryfing if it ROCCC(s)

The dataset I am using as a benchmark comes from Kaggle and can be downloaded here. It contains information about FitBit tracker, a benchmark device for Bellabeats Time.

Is the dataset:

  • Reliable?

The sample is limited to only 30 original users. It doesnt contain any sensitive data about users gender, location, or age. The dataset was originally collected from a random group of FitBit users. They all willingly shared their data with the authors of FitBit Fitness Tracker Data. My initial impression is that a larger sample is needed to achieve reliable results. Perhaps even 10x larger than FitBit Fitness Tracker Data.

  • Original?

Yes, we can locate the original public data.

  • Comprehensive?

Yes, it contains more than a solid amount of .csv files with numerous metrics to pick for analysis.

  • Current?

The original data comes from 2016. That might be problematic and might not fully represent trends of using wearable fitness devices.

  • Cited?

Yes, the source, creator and terms of use are easily available.

In this analysis, I am going to use Spreadsheets to identify primary datasets. Next, I am going to use R programming to analyze the data further and visualize it.

Step 3: Prepare

The dataset I have downloaded from Kaggle includes both wide and long data. It consists of 18 different .csv files in total, each offering in-depth metrics about users heart rate, sleep monitoring, calories burned, the minute-level output of physical activity & the intensity of physical activity, just to name a few. This dataset does not include users private data, such as Name, Surname, Gender, or Address.

Since my task is to focus on only one product from Bellabeats product line, I have picked Bellabeats smartwatch, Time. Apart from telling time it tracks customers activity and sleep patterns and feeds that information to a dedicated app that shares insights with its owner.

I am going to analyze the following datasets:

  • dailyActivity_merged.csv (merged data of calories, intensities, and steps)
  • sleepDay_merged.csv
  • weightLogInfo_merged.csv

Firstly, I would like to address the possible limitations of data. As I have mentioned before, the 30 users sample size might be a great underrepresentation of Fitbit users I am using as a benchmark for my analysis. Furthermore, original data is 5 years old and trends of using wearable smart fitness devices may have changed.

There are also some ridiculous distances logged into TotalDistance in dailyActivity_merged.csv, one cannot travel 40k+ miles/kilometers in a single day. That would mean a person has to move at the speed of 1833km/h or 509m/s. There are 14 such instances. I have discovered that using the countif function.

=COUNTIF(D:D; ">50")

That is an error in data. Fortunately, the neighboring column, TrackerDistance has the same values as TotalDistance. To avoid data duplication I have decided to get rid of the TotalDistance column entirely.

Thank concludes the Spreadsheets part of analysis.

Step 5: Process

daily_activity

  • Remove missing values
  • Remove duplicates
  • Rename ActivityDate to Date
  • Change Date column from character to date type
  • Create new column with Weekdays
  • Create new column TotalActiveMinutes summing up all active minutes
#Duplicates
sum(duplicated(daily_activity))

#Missing values
sum(is.na(daily_activity))

#Rename ActivityDate to Date
colnames(daily_activity)[colnames(daily_activity) == "ActivityDate"] <- "Date"

#Format character to date type
daily_activity$Date <-  as.Date(daily_activity$Date,format='%m/%d/%Y') 

#Add new column Weekdays
daily_activity$Weekdays <- wday(daily_activity$Date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)

#Add new column with total active minutes
daily_activity2 <- daily_activity %>% 
  mutate(TotalActiveMinutes = VeryActiveMinutes + FairlyActiveMinutes + LightlyActiveMinutes)

#Confirm changes
str(daily_activity2)
View(daily_activity2)

First Conclusions

Looking at the merged dataset, we can see that data was logged for 31 days. Comparing SedentaryMinutes Max. value of 1440.0 to LightlyActive and VeryActive Max. values - 518.0 and 210.0 respectively - we can deduce that most users are neither professional sportspeople nor lead very active lifestyles. Moreover, if we look at the Mean WeightKg = 72.04, one might assume that the majority of users are women.

This is because, according to this CDC report, in the years 2015-2016 (the year the original dataset was collected) women aged 20 and more had a mean weight in KG of 77.3 (vs 72.04KG in FitBit users) in the United States. It might mean that said users do not need diet recommendations.

Furthermore, looking at the TotalMinutesAsleep column in my merged dataset we can see that the mean amount of minutes asleep = 419.5 which is equal to roughly 7 hours of sleep. According to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services Most adults need 7 or more hours of good-quality sleep on a regular schedule each night. Getting enough sleep isnt only about total hours of sleep. Its also important to get good-quality sleep on a regular schedule, so you feel rested when you wake up.

Additionally, the mean amount of TotalSteps is roughly 7.7k steps per day which is less than enough for a healthy adult, according to the CDCs report. The goal should be 10k per day.

Initial Inference

Bellabeat might want to implement a feature that notifies users if they dont sleep enough or encourage them to walk more.

Step 6: Analyze

Plotting Auto vs Manual reports of weight data

It could be interesting to discover how dedicated are FitBit users when it comes to reporting their weight. The following plot shows the the distribution of Auto Report vs.Manual Report by type:

report_method_name <- c("Manual Report","Auto Report")
report_method_T_F <- c(length(which(weight$IsManualReport =="TRUE")),length(which(weight$IsManualReport =="FALSE")))
manual_report_or_not <- data.frame(report_method_name,report_method_T_F)
ggplot(manual_report_or_not, aes(report_method_name,report_method_T_F)) +
  geom_bar(stat= "identity", fill="blue")+ 
  geom_text(aes(label=report_method_T_F), vjust=3, color="white", size=5)+
  labs(title="Weight Log Methods by Types",  x= "Weight Log Methods", y="Number of Records")

Inference

Looking at this data viz we can observe that even though there are only 8 distinct Ids in the weight set, 61.1% of reports are manual. It might be that users need more encouragement to report their weight.

Plotting calories burned vs.steps taken

Unsurprisingly, there is a positive correlation - the more steps you take, the more calories you burn. To be even more confident about this conclusion, we can check the correlation between these two variables using the Pearson Correlation Coefficient.

cor.test(merged_final_df$TotalSteps, merged_final_df$Calories, method = 'pearson', conf.level = 0.95)
data:  merged_final_df$TotalSteps and merged_activity_sleep_weight$Calories

alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.5477433 0.6309576

    cor 
0.59092

As we can see, the correlation between the variables is almost 0.6. It means that there is a strong relationship between them.

Plotting activity distribution among users

To discover an activity trend, I am going to plot a wheel chart to showcase activity distribution among users:

daily_activity2 %>% 
  select(VeryActiveMinutes, 
         FairlyActiveMinutes, 
         LightlyActiveMinutes, 
         SedentaryMinutes) %>% 
  summarise(across(everything(), list(sum))) %>% 
  gather(active_level, minutes) %>% 
  mutate(active_level = factor(active_level, 
                               labels = c('Moderate Activity','Light Activity',
                                          'Sedentary','Heavy Activity'))) %>% 
  hchart('pie', hcaes(x = active_level, y = minutes)) %>% 
  hc_title(text = "Distribution of daily activity level in minutes") %>% 
  hc_tooltip(pointFormat = "<b>Value:</b> {point.y} <br>
                 <b>Percentage</b> {point.percentage:,.2f}%")

Activity Distribution

  • Sedentary: 81.33%

  • Light Activity: 15.82%

  • Moderate Activity: 1.11%

  • Heavy Activity: 1.74%

Inference

It seems like Fitbit users are mostly inactive people. Maybe they wear them purely for their aesthetics?

Plotting sleep distribution

Now, to visualize my previous assumption about FitBits users and their sleep patterns and habits, I am going to plot their sleep distribution to showcase whether or not they get enough sleep.

sleep %>%
  select(TotalMinutesAsleep) %>%
  drop_na () %>%
  mutate(sleep_quality = ifelse(TotalMinutesAsleep <= 420, 'Less than 7h',
                         ifelse(TotalMinutesAsleep <= 540, '7h to 9h',
                                'More than 9h'))) %>%
  mutate(sleep_quality = factor(sleep_quality,
                                levels = c('Less than 7h', '7h to 9h', 'More than 9h'))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = TotalMinutesAsleep, fill = sleep_quality)) +
  geom_histogram(position = 'dodge', bins = 30) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = c(.8, .8),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.spacing.y = unit(0, "mm"),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA),
        legend.background = element_blank(),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(colour = "black")) +
  labs(title = "Sleep distribution",
       x = "Time slept (minutes)",
       y = "Count")

Inference

By looking at this data viz, we can see that FitBit users follow regular and healthy sleep patterns, between 6-9 hours of sleep per day. Most users are up to CDCs standards when it comes to getting enough rest.

Relationship between sleep and distance covered

I want to find out whats the relationship between how much FitBit users walk and how well they sleep. If you walk more, do you also sleep more? If you do cover less ground on foot does it mean that you sleep better? Lets investigate:

merged_final_df %>%
  select(Id, TotalDistance, TotalMinutesAsleep) %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarise_all(list(~mean(., na.rm=TRUE))) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(Id = factor(Id)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = Id, y = TotalDistance), stat = "identity", fill = 'lightblue', color = 'black') +
  geom_point(aes(x = Id, y = TotalMinutesAsleep/60), color = 'red') +
  geom_segment(aes(x = Id, xend = Id, y = 0, yend = TotalMinutesAsleep/60), color = 'red', group = 1) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 12), name = "Total Distance",
                     sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*60, name = "Sleep in minutes")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.title.y.right = element_text(color = "red"),
        axis.ticks.y.right = element_line(color = "red"),
        axis.text.y.right = element_text(color = "red")) +
  labs(title = "Average distance vs average sleep by user",
       x = "Users")

Inference

Looking at the plot above, one cannot in my opinion say, that there is a clear relationship between the distance you travel on foot per day and sleep pattern. That is, on average, at least.

Plotting sleep vs minutes in bed, to find out if the difference between actual sleep and minutes spent in bed

I want to find out if our users like to spend more time in their beds than necessary. First, I want to learn whats the difference between the time users spend sleeping and time they spend in their beds:

sleep_activity <- sleep %>%
  mutate(TimeAwakeInBed = TotalTimeInBed - TotalMinutesAsleep)

Now, lets plot the difference:

ggplot(sleep_activity, aes(x=TimeAwakeInBed)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), binwidth=30, alpha=0.6)+
  geom_density(alpha=0.2, fill="blue") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(TimeAwakeInBed)), color="red", linetype="dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=max(TimeAwakeInBed)), color="red", linetype="dashed") +
  annotate(geom="text", x=39 + 55, y = 0.02, size = 7, label = "mean = 39") +
  annotate(geom="text", x=371 - 50, y = 0.02, size = 7, label = "max = 371") +
  labs(x= "Time Awake in Bed", y="Density")

Looking at this data viz, we can observe that FitBit users spend arguably too much time in bed. They spend on average 39 minutes awake in bed, which is not that bad, frankly, but could be improved. A tiny portion spends even more time, sometimes more than 200 minutes.

How many minutes during weekdays users are active?

To answer that question, I am going to plot a different activity charts during weekdays:

average_very_active_minutes <- daily_activity2 %>% 
  group_by(Weekdays) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(VeryActiveMinutes),
               list(VeryActiveMinutes = mean))

average_fairly_active_minutes <- daily_activity2 %>% 
  group_by(Weekdays) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(FairlyActiveMinutes),
               list(FairlyActiveMinutes = mean))

average_lightly_active_minutes <- daily_activity2 %>% 
  group_by(Weekdays) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(LightlyActiveMinutes),
               list(LightlyActiveMinutes = mean))

average_total_active_minutes <- daily_activity2 %>% 
  group_by(Weekdays) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(TotalActiveMinutes),
               list(TotalActiveMinutes = mean))

average_activity_minutes <- merge(average_very_active_minutes,average_fairly_active_minutes,by=c("Weekdays"))

average_activity_minutes1 <- merge(average_activity_minutes,average_lightly_active_minutes, by=c("Weekdays"))


average_activity_minutes %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x="Weekdays",y = average_activity_minutes,fill=type)) + geom_boxplot(outlier.colour = 'red', outlier.shape = 8)+
  theme(legend.position = 'none') +
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="point", shape=21, size=4)


very_active_chart <- ggplot(average_activity_minutes1, aes(x=Weekdays,y=VeryActiveMinutes, group=1))+

Inference

We can see that FitBit users record the highest activity on Mondays and Saturdays. On the other hand, Sundays and Thursdays are the least active days.

It could be due to the busy start of the week on Mondays and outdoor/social activities on Saturdays. It might be a good idea for Bellabeat to send notifications on Wednesdays and Fridays to take up some physical activities.

Step 7: Share

Having analyzed the FitBit Tracker dataset I can say that people who use wearable technology are:

  • Moderately fit, by all means, they are not professional sportspeople
  • They live mostly sedentary lifestyles, probably working office jobs
  • They sleep enough but tend to spend more time in bed than necessary
  • Their most active days are Mondays, Tuesdays, and Saturdays, whereas least active are Thursdays and Sundays

Additionally

  • Unsurprisingly, the more you walk, the more calories one burns through the day.
  • There is no correlation between the distance users travel on foot and the amount of sleep they get.
  • Unfortunately, the weight dataset is too scarce to analyze and draw conclusions from it properly. Collecting a larger dataset is needed.
  • Overall integrity of dataset could be increased, for example, by collecting data from a larger sample of the user population.

Step 8: Act

In terms of a recommendation for Bellabeat regarding their business model and their smartwatch, Time, Bellabeat could:

  • Keep making a stylish product since benchmark analysis shows that most users use it as a trendy gadget rather than a fitness device

  • Keep developing the UX for an app that pairs with Time smartwatch. Better UX might encourage users to manually report their weight data. This could be rewarded by introducing an Achievements feature where a users can keep track of their progress if they are aiming to loose weight or get more fit in general

  • Consider introducing features and non-intrusive notifications to remind users about healthy sleep patterns, activity time, or to get out of bed as soon as they wake up

  • Recommend health and fitness articles via their Bellabeat app to motivate users

  • Send reminders to encourage healthy habits and routines before and after sleep hours and further promote mindfulness

  • Send notifications to encourage users to walk more, at least try to achieve the recommended 10k steps per day.

  • Introduce a feature that allows users to set goals based on Bellabeats recommendations in terms of sleep, calories burned, and activity time

  • It would be interesting to learn if users have trouble falling asleep or trouble getting out of bed. How can Bellabeat obtain such data?

  • I believe it would be exciting if the Bellabeat app could connect with the smartphone camera and match steps taken with photos taken on a particular day. It could create a bond between users and their Bellabeat device/software.

Thak you for your time :)
